"""
rel_types — shared reliability-engine leaf: the RelAction verdict, the narrow
observation structs, the per-policy state structs, and the two mount bundles.

Contract: doc/05_design/hardware/nand_recovery/recovery_algorithms_design.md §1
(implements architecture doc reliability_engine_architecture.md §3). This module is
a PURE-POLICY LEAF: it does `use nvme_types.*` + `use nd_types.*` ONLY — never
fil/ftl — so both fil.spl and ftl.spl (and every rel_* policy module) may import it
without a cycle (design §0 / architecture §0 LAW). No module holds a Fil/Ftl handle;
policies are pure functions over these structs returning a RelAction verdict, and
the mounting layer actuates.

Module-boundary law (design §1, §9 L1; confirmed against the guide's routing rule):
this L1 leaf owns exactly the STRUCT DECLARATIONS + the RelAction kind constants +
the two constructors the design doc explicitly places in §1 (`rel_action`,
`rel_read_obs`). It deliberately provides NO per-policy state-struct constructors:
the design doc places `rel_ladder_state_new`/phase constants in §2 (rel_ladder.spl,
L4) and defines the vref/refresh/disturb/wear/health mutators in §3-§7 (their own
policy lanes L2-L7). Those lanes own their `*_new`/decision/mutator fns; a zero-init
state struct is built with the plain struct-literal constructor
(`RelVrefCache(offset: ..., valid: ..., gen: ...)`, language.md "Constructors:
Point(x: 3, y: 4)"). Keeping constructors in their lanes means zero duplicate-symbol
collision when L2-L7 land.

Language landmines honored (design §0):
- Rel prefix on every public type (interpreter global-registry collision guard,
  mirrors nand_emu's Ne prefix and nd_types' Nd prefix).
- RelAction is a tagged struct {kind:i64, arg:i64}, NOT an enum-with-payload: a
  payload enum can tag-decay across the rel_ladder -> mount module boundary; the
  tagged struct round-trips identically (architecture §3 detail-design gate, design
  §9 L1). kind and arg stay raw i64 — arg is the flat boundary value (a block index
  OR a signed Vref offset depending on kind) that feeds the FTL/FIL flat-i64 world.
- Per-block state is a dense [i64] array of length NUM_BLOCKS (= 64), indexed by
  physical block — no Dict (design §0 "No Dict.get-as-Option").
- Return-the-object: policy lanes' mutators RETURN the updated struct (value types);
  this leaf holds no mutators.

Typed-dimensions law (guide "TYPED DIMENSIONS LAW"): a SCALAR field that is a NAND
physical block/page coordinate uses the nd_types.spl value-type newtype rather than
a raw i64. Here that is exactly `RelBlockObs.blk` and `RelLadderState.blk` -> NdBlock
(field name kept from the design doc). RelAction.arg stays flat i64 (it is the
round-trip boundary value, polymorphic in meaning). The dense per-block [i64] arrays
stay [i64]: the block is the ARRAY INDEX (a flat i64), the stored VALUES are
offsets/counts/seqs/flags/page-estimates, and the §5/§6 policy pseudocode assigns
raw i64 into them (e.g. rel_disturb_observe's `out.hot_page[blk] = page`) — wrapping
those arrays in a newtype would break that pseudocode for zero coordinate-safety
gain. Consequence for L4 (rel_ladder.spl): because RelLadderState.blk is an NdBlock,
L4 must convert at the flat boundary when it emits a verdict, i.e.
`rel_action(rel_act_calibrate(), s.blk.idx)` — exactly the TYPED-DIMS "convert at the
flat-ppn boundary with existing fw code" rule.
"""

use nvme_types.*
use nd_types.*

# ── 1.1  The verdict — RelAction tagged struct ────────────────────────────────
# Exactly the seven RelAction variants named in architecture §3
# (Accept / RetryAtOffset / CalibrateBlock / MarkForRefresh / ReclaimNow /
# Quarantine / Uncorrectable), encoded as the fallback tagged struct the
# architecture mandates.
struct RelAction:
    kind: i64      # one of the rel_act_* codes below
    arg:  i64      # block index or signed Vref offset, per kind

# kind codes — fn-returning constants (freestanding-safe; no module-level init)
fn rel_act_accept() -> i64:
    0              # Accept: data good / no action

fn rel_act_retry() -> i64:
    1              # RetryAtOffset: arg = signed Vref offset; FIL re-sense

fn rel_act_calibrate() -> i64:
    2              # CalibrateBlock: arg = blk; FIL persist winning offset (ROR)

fn rel_act_refresh() -> i64:
    3              # MarkForRefresh: arg = blk; FTL enqueue age/error rewrite (FCR/DEAR)

fn rel_act_reclaim() -> i64:
    4              # ReclaimNow: arg = blk; FTL reclaim_block (disturb/wear)

fn rel_act_quarantine() -> i64:
    5              # Quarantine: arg = blk; FTL retire + alloc_spare

fn rel_act_uncorrectable() -> i64:
    6              # Uncorrectable: arg = blk; ladder exhausted -> host NAND_ECC_FAIL

fn rel_action(kind: i64, arg: i64) -> RelAction:
    RelAction(kind: kind, arg: arg)

# ── 1.2  Observation structs (narrow, pure inputs) ────────────────────────────
struct RelReadObs:          # one sense result, fed to rel_ladder_step
    code:      i64          # ECC_OK (0) | NAND_ECC_FAIL (nvme_types constant)
    corrected: i64          # coarse 0 / 1 / 2 (2 = uncorrectable) — the ECC-signal constraint
    offset:    i64          # signed Vref offset this sense used (vref = 128 + offset)
    depth:     i64          # rung index of this observation

struct RelBlockObs:         # per-block snapshot, caller-assembled, fed to FTL policies
    blk:              NdBlock   # typed physical block coordinate (was i64 in design §1.2)
    erase_count:      i64       # from Fil.erase_count
    rd_disturb:       i64       # EXISTING ftl.spl rd_disturb counter (source of truth)
    corrected_events: i64       # from RelHealth (count of reads with corrected>=1)
    last_prog_seq:    i64       # RelRefreshState
    cur_seq:          i64       # ftl next_seq (logical clock, §4 age proxy)

fn rel_read_obs(code: i64, corrected: i64, offset: i64, depth: i64) -> RelReadObs:
    RelReadObs(code: code, corrected: corrected, offset: offset, depth: depth)

# ── 1.3  Per-policy state structs (dense [i64], length NUM_BLOCKS = 64) ────────
# Constructors + mutators live in the policy lanes (rel_ladder/rel_vref/rel_refresh/
# rel_disturb/rel_wear/rel_health); this leaf declares the shapes only.
struct RelLadderState:      # one live instance per in-flight read (scalars)
    blk:            NdBlock  # typed physical block under recovery (was i64 in design §2)
    depth:          i64      # rungs consumed (0 = clean; observability retry-depth)
    table_idx:      i64      # next rel_vref table entry to try
    best_offset:    i64      # winning offset (for CalibrateBlock)
    best_corrected: i64      # coarse corrected count at the winner
    phase:          i64      # rel_phase_seed(0) -> table(1) -> done(2)/fail(3) [constants in L4]

struct RelVrefCache:        # per-block calibrated Vref offset (ROR-lite, §3)
    offset: [i64]           # calibrated Vref offset per block (0 = none)
    valid:  [i64]           # 1 = calibrated, 0 = not/expired
    gen:    [i64]           # erase generation at calibration (audit / optional gen-guard)

struct RelRefreshState:     # FCR/DEAR-lite refresh bookkeeping (§4)
    last_prog_seq: [i64]    # next_seq snapshot at the block's last (re)write
    marked:        [i64]    # 1 = already queued for refresh (dedupe)

struct RelDisturbState:     # STRAW-lite read-disturb hottest-page estimate (§5)
    hot_page:  [i64]        # Boyer-Moore majority candidate page per block
    hot_count: [i64]        # its running majority count

struct RelWearState:        # SREA-lite dwell-aware static wear leveling (§6)
    last_global_erase: [i64]  # total_erases snapshot when this block was last erased

struct RelHealth:           # observability sink, durable at RelFtlMount.health (§7)
    reads:            [i64]  # total reads per block
    corrected_sum:    [i64]  # sum of coarse corrected counts (for scaled RBER ppm)
    corrected_events: [i64]  # count of reads with corrected>=1 (FCR trigger source)
    retry_depth_max:  [i64]  # deepest recovery-ladder rung observed
    refresh_cause:    [i64]  # rel_cause_* tag of the last refresh (constants in L2)

# ── 1.4  Mount bundles (pure state, composed by the layer — no handle) ────────
# Health-sink discipline (design §1.4 / architecture §5): RelFtlMount.health is the
# DURABLE sink; RelFilMount.health is a TRANSIENT in-loop copy for the read in
# flight — the FIL copy never accumulates across reads. On read completion the
# (corrected, retry_depth) ride up to ftl.read, which folds them into the durable
# RelFtlMount.health via rel_health_note_read (L2).
struct RelFilMount:         # device-near mount (recovery ladder + vref calibration)
    vref:   RelVrefCache
    health: RelHealth
    ladder: RelLadderState

struct RelFtlMount:         # map-owning mount (refresh + disturb + wear + durable health)
    refresh: RelRefreshState
    disturb: RelDisturbState
    wear:    RelWearState
    health:  RelHealth
